Analysis of temporal trends in southern resident killer whales

This is version 0.18.07.31.

1 Requirements

All analyses require the R software (v3.4+) for data retrieval, data processing, and summarizing model results. We also need a few packages that are not included with the base installation of R, so we begin by installing them (if necessary) and then loading them.

if(!require("here")) {
  install.packages("here")
  library("here")
}
if(!require("readr")) {
  install.packages("readr")
  library("readr")
}
if(!require("ggplot2")) {
  install.packages("ggplot2")
  library("ggplot2")
}
## set directory locations
datadir <- here("data")
analdir <- here("analysis")

2 Data

2.1 Southern resident killer whales

The counts of southern resident killer whales (SRKW) come from the Center for Whale Research, and are broken down by the three major groups: J, K and L pods.

kw <- read_csv(file.path(datadir, "SRKW.csv"))
head(kw)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##    year     J     K     L   JKL
##   <int> <int> <int> <int> <int>
## 1  1976    16    15    40    71
## 2  1977    18    16    46    80
## 3  1978    18    16    46    80
## 4  1979    19    16    47    82
## 5  1980    19    16    49    84
## 6  1981    19    16    47    82
n_yr <- nrow(kw)

2.2 Snake River spring Chinook

The counts of Snake River spring Chinook at Lower Granite Dam come from Columbia Basin Research. I’ll divide them by 1000 to make them more similar in magnitude to the SRKW data.

ss <- read_csv(file.path(datadir, "SRSS.csv"))
ss[,2] <- ss[,2]/1000
head(ss)
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##    year  SRSS
##   <int> <dbl>
## 1  1976 20.5 
## 2  1977 38.8 
## 3  1978 41.0 
## 4  1979  7.54
## 5  1980  5.46
## 6  1981 13.1

2.3 Puget Sound Chinook

ps_raw <- read_csv(file.path(datadir, "PS_Chin.csv"))
head(ps_raw)
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
##   popn           year spawners
##   <chr>         <int>    <int>
## 1 Cascade River  2013      316
## 2 Cascade River  2012      495
## 3 Cascade River  2011      269
## 4 Cascade River  2010      337
## 5 Cascade River  2009      343
## 6 Cascade River  2008      289
ps <- aggregate(spawners ~ year, data = ps_raw, sum)
plot(ps[,1], ps[,2], type="l")

3 Plots

Here are plots of the time series of counts for orcas and salmon.

par(mfrow=c(2,1), mai=c(0.8,0.8,0.2,0), omi=rep(0.1,4))
clr <- rev(viridis::viridis(4, end = 0.8))
## orcas
matplot(kw[,1], kw[,-1], type="l", lty="solid", xlim = c(kw[[1,1]], 2018),
        xlab = "", ylab = "Count", col = clr)
text(2018,kw[nrow(kw),-1],c("J","K","L","All"), cex=0.9, col = clr)
mtext("Southern resident killer whales", 3, adj=0, line=0.5)
## salmon
matplot(ss[,1], ss[,2], type="l", lty="solid", xlim = c(kw[[1,1]], 2018),
     xlab = "Year", ylab = "Count (1000s)", col = viridis::viridis(1))
mtext("Snake River spring Chinook", 3, adj=0, line=0.5)

It is perhaps more informative to look at the year-to-year differences in the counts of SRKW, as that gives an indication as to whether births exceed deaths.

## difference ts
kwd <- apply(kw[,2:4], 2, diff)
par(mai=c(0.8,0.8,0.2,0), omi=rep(0.1,4))
matplot(kw[-1,1], kwd, type="l", lty="solid",
        xlab = "", ylab = "Count", col = clr)

4 Correlations

Here are the correlations among the differenced counts of SRKW and SRSS Chinook.

## raw counts of Chinook
round(cor(x = ss[-n_yr,2], y = kwd), 2)
##         J    K    L
## SRSS 0.07 0.24 0.06
## log counts of Chinook
round(cor(x = log(ss[-n_yr,2]), y = kwd), 2)
##         J    K    L
## SRSS 0.11 0.23 0.09
